Reviewer 1

1b.

“62.2% of 2902 WT exons in SNV library have index > 0.80. This seems low given these exons are represented in the exome-sequencing data (ExAC).”

The percentage of included WT exons > 0.80 at 91% in the SNV library. The 62.% we state is from the SRE library. My numbers show that 58% (2882/4920) of WT exons have index > 0.80 and and 67% (3297/4920) > 0.50 in the DHFR backbone. The reviewer misunderstood the number, which we can make more clear.

1c

How comparable are the DHFR and SMN1 backbone, we mention that DHFR is more reproducible.

sre_data %>% 
    filter(!is.na(index_dhfr)) %>% nrow() %>% print()

Fig 1E. shows correlatin of 0.94 for DHFR biological replicates, 0.89 for SMN1, and shows correlation between the two is 0.85. We actually recover more sequences with SMN1 than DHFR, but choose DHFR for it’s replicability. I’m not sure what further evidence could show that the results are generalizable across backbones.
